The main aim of this thesis is to determine possible variations in
the telluric microbial community, comparing two agricultural systems
(i.e. organic and conventional). Additionally, we aim to evaluate the impacts
of three differents primary processes: plowing,
ripping and disk-harrowing, considering also the seasonality (Autumn and Spring)

This work is part of the project \emph{Montepaldi Long Term Experiment}
(MoLTE) conducted by the University of Florence. MoLTE is a long term
experiment established in 1991 on agricultural soils of Montepaldi
farm, near San Casciano Val di Pesa (Florence).

To analyze the edaphic micro-fauna and -flora, the biochemical method
of fatty derivated from phospholipids of membran (\acs{PLFA}) has been used,
since these acids are specific to different microbial groups.

Results from statistical analysis did not show significant
variation nor between the two agricultural systems, neither with regards
to the three different prymary processes.
Significant differences were only found when comparing profiles obtained 
of microbial
communities collected in different seasons.
